comments.body:
For what it's worth, here's the comparison of peduncle lengths from the FNA treatment:

Ratibida peduncularis: Peduncles 14–45+ cm (ribs tan, prominent).

Ratibida columnifera: Peduncles (1.5–)6.5–48+ cm (ribs tan, prominent).

And for completeness on leaves, I think these are the coastal var. picta:

https://prc-symbiota.tacc.utexas.edu/symbiota/prc/images/_TEX/TEX00414838_lg.jpg

https://prc-symbiota.tacc.utexas.edu/symbiota/prc/images/_TEX/TEX00008816.jpg

https://prc-symbiota.tacc.utexas.edu/symbiota/prc/images/_LL/LL00414850_lg.jpg

It really looks Correll & Johnston's peduncle character is not useful, but leaves'll get you there fairly reliably if there aren't any handy stigmas or fruits to look at. I think most of the iNaturalist "peduncularis" are misidentified columnifera.

Interesting. I've never heard of Ratibida peduncularis, and it has never been reported in New Mexico, so far as I can tell. 

Poking at things a bit and checking against SEINet (swbiodiversity.org/seinet/) and the Flora of North America (http://www.efloras.org/florataxon.aspx?flora_id=1&taxon_id=128007), I think the treatment in Correll & Johnston is incorrect. The FNA treatment doesn't use peduncle differences in the key, and the descriptions of the two species don't indicate any difference in that character. The characters used in the FNA to separate the two have to do with the stigmas & fruits; I don't have stigmas handy for this guy, but in fruit characters is seems to fall nicely in columnifera. Here are a couple of comparison pictures from wildflower.org; Ratibida columnifera:

https://www.wildflower.org/image_archive/640x480/NSI/NSI_IMG00247.JPG

Ratibida peduncularis:

https://www.wildflower.org/image_archive/640x480/NSI/NSI_IMG00249.JPG

It also looks like the leaves in Ratibida peduncularis var. peduncularis are pretty distinctive compared to Ratibida columnifera: twice-pinnatifid vs. once-pinnatifid. The other variety of Ratibida peduncularis, var. picta, is strictly coastal according to FNA, so if it gets into NM it seems like it'd have to be var. peduncularis. Comparison from SEINet; Ratibida columnifera:

http://sweetgum.nybg.org/images3/884/732/1742206.jpg

Ratibida peduncularis:

https://prc-symbiota.tacc.utexas.edu/symbiota/prc/images/_TEX/TEX00414837_lg.jpg

The leaves aren't as clear as we might like for my observation, but they sure look once-pinnatifid to me.
